  "slug": "barszcz-czerwony",
  "title": "Barszcz Czerwony",
  "subtitle": "Polish red borscht",
  "excerpt": "Clear, jewel-red beetroot broth seasoned with bay, allspice, and a sharp hit of vinegar. Drunk from a cup or served in a bowl with a small uszka (tiny mushroom-filled dumplings) on Christmas Eve.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Barszcz czerwony (red borscht) is one of the oldest dishes in Polish cooking. The clear version, barszcz czysty, served with uszka is the traditional first course of Wigilia (Christmas Eve dinner). Documented in Maria Lemnis and Henryk Vitry, Old Polish Traditions in the Kitchen and at the Table (1979) and Lesley Chamberlain, The Food and Cooking of Eastern Europe (1989).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The colour is everything in barszcz. A good barszcz is a deep, translucent ruby, not brown, not murky, not grey. To keep it vibrant, the soup must never boil hard after the beetroot goes in (heat destroys the pigment), and a splash of vinegar or lemon juice is essential: acid stabilises the colour and sharpens the flavour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "This recipe makes a clear, clean barszcz. For the traditional Christmas Eve version, strain out all the solids after cooking and serve as a consommé-style broth. For a more filling everyday version, leave the vegetables in or blend a portion back in.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
